@Composable
fun BrokenRecomposition() {
    // 1. Creating unstable lambda every recomposition
    Button(onClick = { count++ }) {  // Creates new lambda each time
        Text("Click")
    }

    // 2. Using expensive computation without remember
    val result = expensiveCalculation()  // Runs every recomposition

    // 3. Forgetting keys in lists
    items.forEach { item ->
        Text(item.text)  // No key, unstable
    }

    // 4. Side effect in composition
    val db = Database.getInstance()  // Runs every recomposition

    // 5. Recursive recomposition
    var count by remember { mutableStateOf(0) }
    Text("Count: $count")
    if (count < 10) {
        // This creates infinite recomposition!
        count++
    }
}

phase2.explanation:
🤖 **Common recomposition mistakes and how to fix them.**

| Mistake | Fix |
|---------|-----|
| Unstable lambda | Use `remember { { action } }` |
| Expensive computation | Use `remember { compute() }` |
| No keys in list | Use `items.forEach { Text(key = it.id) }` |
| Side effects in composition | Use `LaunchedEffect` or `SideEffect` |
| Infinite recomposition | Don't modify state during composition |

**Fixes:**
```kotlin
// 1. Stabilize lambda
val onIncrement = remember { { count++ } }
Button(onClick = onIncrement) {
    Text("Click")
}

// 2. Remember expensive computation
val result = remember { expensiveCalculation() }

// 3. Add keys
items.forEach { item ->
    Text(
        text = item.text,
        key = item.id
    )
}

// 4. Use effect for side effects
LaunchedEffect(Unit) {
    val db = Database.getInstance()
}

// 5. Don't modify state in composition
// State changes should only happen in callbacks
```

**Kotlin-chan says:**
"Stable composables = efficient recomposition. Use remember wisely."

